SIMPLE: scant
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scant
<hw>Scant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Scanter</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Scantest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[Icel. <ets>skamt</ets>, neuter of
<ets>skamr</ets>, <ets>skammr</ets>, short; cf. <ets>skamta</ets> to
dole out, to portion.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not full, large, or
plentiful; scarcely sufficient; less than is wanted for the purpose;
scanty; meager; not enough; <as>as, a <ex>scant</ex> allowance of
provisions or water; a <ex>scant</ex> pattern of cloth for a
garment</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His sermon was <qex>scant</qex>, in all, a quarter of an hour.</q>
<rj><qau>Ridley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Sparing; parsimonious; chary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be somewhat <qex>scanter</qex> of your maiden presence.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See under <er>Scanty</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scant
<hw>Scant</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Scanted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Scanting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To limit; to
straiten; to treat illiberally; to stint; <as>as, to <ex>scant</ex> one
in provisions; to <ex>scant</ex> ourselves in the use of
necessaries</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where a man hath a great living laid together and where he is
<qex>scanted</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am <qex>scanted</qex> in the pleasure of dwelling on your
actions.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cut short; to make small, narrow, or scanty; to
curtail.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Scant</xex> not my cups.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Scant
<hw>Scant</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To fail, or become less; to
scantle; <as>as, the wind <ex>scants</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Scant
<hw>Scant</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a scant manner; with difficulty;
scarcely; hardly.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So weak that he was <qex>scant</qex> able to go down the
stairs.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Scant
<hw>Scant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Scantness; scarcity.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>T. Carew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scantily</ent>⟦br⟧
